# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1897-louisville-colonels-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1882 Louisville Eclipse season** was the first season as a Major League club for the franchise.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The team, which had played for several years as a semi-pro team, joined the new American Association league.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] They finished the season with a 42–38 record, good for third place.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1883 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 52–45 record, fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1884 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 68–40 record, third place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] There has been some debate over whom the manager of this club was, with some sources listing the club's starting second baseman, Joe Gerhardt, as manager for at least part of the year, with others crediting team official Mike Walsh with either all or part of the year.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] Guy Hecker started 75 games for the Eclipse in 1884 and won the American Association Pitching Triple Crown by leading the league in wins, with 52, strikeouts, with 385, and earned run average with 1.80.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The **1885 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The team (formerly the Louisville Eclipse) finished with a 53–59 record, tied for fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1886-louisville-colonels-season] The **1886 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1886-louisville-colonels-season] The team finished with a 66–70 record, fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1887-louisville-colonels-season] The **1887 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1887-louisville-colonels-season] The team finished with a 76–60 record, fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The **1888 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The team was coming off a strong 1887 season, in which it won 76 games and lost 60 under new manager John "Kick" Kelly, but the 1888 season proved to be a disappointment.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The team's primary problem was a lack of quality pitching.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The best pitcher, Thomas "Toad" Ramsey, had won 37 games in 1887; in 1888, plagued by a sore arm, he won only 8.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] None of the other pitchers proved capable of picking up the slack.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The 1888 Colonels finished with a 58–87 record, seventh place in the American Association.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] On June 7, shareholder Mordecai Davidson bought out most of the other shareholders, appointing himself president and John R.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] Two days later, he officially took over as manager as well.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] John Kerins, among others, served as team captain, guiding the team's on-field activities.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The most famous member of the 1888 Colonels was outfielder Pete Browning, a ferocious hitter who was noted for excessive drinking and peculiar behavior.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] One of the best-known stories about Browning concerns an incident which occurred in Kansas City on June 19 of the 1888 season.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] Browning got up in a Kansas City hotel that morning, following a heavy rainstorm.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The gutter in front of the hotel had been overwhelmed by the rain; there was a large puddle of water there.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] The drunken Browning purchased some fishing gear and tried his hand at fishing in the gutter.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] It's unclear whether he did this as a joke or whether he really believed that he could catch fish in the gutter, but in any event, the gutter-fishing incident became one of the most often-repeated Pete Browning stories.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1888-louisville-colonels-season] It's documented in the Louisville Courier-Journal.
[src:1897-louisville-colonels-season/1897-louisville-colonels-season] The **1897 Louisville Colonels** baseball team finished with a 52–87 record and eleventh place in the National League.
